<S SAMPLE 1>
<P 173>
[}A DISCOURSE BETWEENE THE BURGUER
AND THE YEAMAN}]
   Ho Yeaman, from whence lead you
that load of wood? that load of fagots,
of great wood, and of logges?
   [$P.$] Sir, I bring it from the wood: I bring 
it from the forrest: I bring it from the field,
from the groue, from the hedges, from the
vnderwood, from the bramble bushes: from
our land towne, from our village, and from
our hammell.
   [$B.$] Is it good? is it dry? is it wood of birch?
is it oaken wood?
   [$P.$] O yea Sir, it burneth well: it burneth like
brimstone.
   [$B.$] Yeamanesse, good wife, haue you no fresh
egges? haue you any ducke egges? some
pullets? some fresh butter? some sweet or
sowre milke? some good sweet creame?
some creamed, or curdded milke? any
churned milke, or new cheese?
   [$P.$] Yes, yes, Sir: O yea! I haue some of all
sorts, and good to eate.
   [$B.$] How much sell you the dozen of fresh
egges? the pound of butter? the pint, or the
pot of your milke?
   [$P.$] Sir, come your wayes and see, and I will
giue you good cheape of all.
   [$B.$] I will, well, let me see it then if it please
you.
   [$P.$] Goe to, come, come: of which doth it
please you to haue Sir?
   [$B.$] I will some of all sorts, measure me, sell
me: make me good measure: measure mee
well: sell me good cheape: ouerprize not
the price thereof: Goe to, take your money:
render me my rest: but how much will you
haue? how much should I giue you? tell
me quickly.
   [$P.$] Sir, you know it well: you know it so
well as I: hold, take women then. Adieu till
I see you againe good wife.
   [$B.$] Ho, speake good wife: hola, speake:
hearke here a little: haue you spunne the fine
flaxe, and the hempe of my Lady, &c. or
mine? haue not you bleached my fine linnen
for to make some shirts? my threed, and
my coorse linnen for to make some sackes;
and some other paultry for mine houshold,
and for to accommodate my children and
my seruants?
   [$P.$] No truly Sir yet: for I haue had no
leasure since: it hath alwayes beene drie
weather since, I assure you.
   [$B.$] Is not yet my corne ripe in the fields?
   [$P.$] Yes Sir, it is long agone: it behoues you
but make ready your worke folkes: but
your mowers, your shearers, and your
cutters of corne.
<P 174>
[^REPETITION OF PREVIOUS UTTERANCE OMITTED HERE.^]
   [$B.$] Haue you fed my horses, and my stoned
horses? my mares, breeding mares, and
colts: my cowes, and my calues? my bulls,
and my beeues? my rammes, sheepe, lambs,
and my ewes? &c.
   [$P.$] Yes Sir, and Madame; all are well.
   [$B.$] My bore, and my hogges, my sowes and
my pigges, do they feed well with oakornes
of oake? with chesnuts, or other graine?
   [$P.$] Ho, ho, Sir, a Sow or a Hog doth eate
of euery thing, though it should bee of a
stone, or of iron.
   [$B.$] Are they in the wood, in the groue, in
the forrest, or in the stie?
   [$P.$] Yea, yea, Sir: O yes! they are alwayes in
the wood.
   [$B.$] Are there any of them eaten with the
wolfe, with the she-wolfe, with the foxe,
with the she-foxe, with the beare, with the
she-beare, or with the badger?
   [$P.$] O no! for they can defend themselues
well with their clawes, with their pawes,
and with their great pointed and sharpe 
teeth.
   [$B.$] What say you? is it possible? truly I
beleeue it not.
   [$P.$] Yea truly it is true: I assure you that it is
very true.
   [$B.$] Is not this here, my caroch, my coach,
my chariot, my cart, and my litter.
   [$P.$] Yes, yes, sir, and all their equipage; as the
harnesse, the furniture, and their
necessities.
   [$B.$] Haue you spanged my horses to the
chariot?
   [$P.$] Yes, Sir, I spanged them the other day
for to carrie some dung, and some dunghill,
for to fatten the land, the yarde, and the
field.
   [$B.$] Well, well, it was well done. Till me the
land well, the fields, and the yards with the
plough, and the harrow: and harrow me
also the land, the field, and the yard, after
that you shall haue ared, sowne, and
accommodated them.
   [$P.$] Sir, I shall not faile to doe it: I shall not
misse to doe it.
   [$B.$] Thresh me well the corne with the flaile
in the barne, on the floore: and fan, riddle,
and make very cleane, my graine, out of his
chaffe, and straw: and chiefly my wheate.
Moreouer, feed well, and take heed to my
Pigeons, Hennes, and Pullets; to my
Peacocke, & to my Peahen: to my Turky cocks,
and to my Turkyhens: and to all their little
chickens: and aboue all to my Doue-coat.
<P 175>
   [$P.$] Sir, there shall be no fault in all that: wee
shall take heed to all.
   [$B.$] Adieu good man, and good wife: God
keepe you from euill.
   [$P.$] Adieu Sir, adieu Madam vntill the next
market day.

[}A DISCOURSE BETWEENE A CAP. AND HIS
INFERIOUR OFFICERS AND 
SOULDJERS.}]
   [$C.$] My Lieutenant, mine Ensigne, my
Serjeans, and my Corporals.
   [$O.$] What doth it please you sir? will you 
haue any thing?
   [$C.$] I beleeue we must march, take our way,
and make a voyage to morrow: that it
behoues vs to beate to the fields one of these
dayes, or very soone.
   [$O.$] Sir where if it please you? in what part
must we goe? march? take our iourney? or 
make our voyage?
   [$C.$] Doe not you know? against the enemy,
in the fields, in the champion field.
   [$O.$] Sir, what sort of enemy? what sort of
folkes be they?
   [$C.$] The Spaniard, the Castilian, the Italian
and the Albanians.
   [$O.$] The ill man breake his armes, the head
and the legges.
   [$C.$] Amen, amen: so be it: so may it happen
vnto him.
   [$O.$] Sir, is he so neere? is hee so nigh? is hee
verie neare?
   [$C.$] Yes, yes: see here he is at hand: behold,
he is here at our flankes: see here hee is
behind vs: see here he is within a shot of a
cannon, of a musket, of a harquebuse, of a pistol,
to vs.
   [$O.$] Then shall it be for his harme, for his
damage, and to his losse.
   [$C.$] Sir, since it is so, cause the horsemen to
aduance, the troops, the men at armes, the
carbins, the dragons, the light horsemen,
the fantassins, the lanciers, the
scoppetiers, the harquebusiers on horsebacke: and
all the other braue Voluntaries that follow
after vs.
   [$O.$] Sir, see here they are all: see here they
come: and are all armed, equipaged and
ready. Behold also the barded horses that
conuoy the cannon, the baggage, and all the
munition, to wit, the powder, the bullets,
the cannon bullets, the match, the cariage,
the harnesse, the attirals, the victuallers, the
pinoniers, the mules, the mulers, the asses,
the nags; and all their equipage: and all
others munition and furniture of war.
   [$C.$] Musketiers, be ready: Pikemen aduance
you to the front, quickly, quickly. Halt:
hold you still without any words: silence.
<P 176>
Giue the word to the Sergeant from hand
to hand. Make them keepe their rankes, and
hold them ready for all occasions.
   [$O.$] Sir, we will doe it, and protest all to die
and liue with you.
   [$C.$] I thanke you my masters: I thanke you
fellowes.
   Have courage my masters: take courage
fellowes: if it please God we shall all be rich:
we shall all be mounted, equipaged, and in
better order to morrow: wee shall well
recompence our long journeyes, and our great
trauell. For the Spaniards haue gold chaines
about their neckes, and great store of
pistols in their purses; without other fine white
money, so well rials, as mattes: and many
other sorts of money very fine and good.
    Sa, sa, prepare you: for they come and tell
vs, That the enemie is here at hand. Do not
ye heare his horses neigh? Light your
matches from hand to hand. Light your matches
at both the ends. Cocke your matches:
bullet in mouth.
   A brace of Sergeants from hand to hand.
Keepe your rankes: to your long order:
silence: no words, momme, halt, halt.
   Musketiers, are ye ready? giue fire, giue
fire. Ho, ho, let vs charge, charge, kill, kill.
Shoot, harquebusiers and musketiers. Haw
pikemen, aduance, aduance: charge, charge,
sa, sa, sa. Let vs giue on, let vs lay vpon those
robbers, for they shall pay very deare their
boldnesse: they shall pay deare their
rashnesse and comming.
   Cut, cut their throats: for euen so well
shall they cut yours, if they abide masters of
the battell, of the Champion field, of the
field, and of our Campe.

[}LITTLE WORDS BETWEENE A SCHOOLE-MASTER,
AND ONE OF HIS SCHOLLERS.}]
   [$E.$] Master, is the French tongue vneasie,
or difficult for to learne.
   [$M.$] No, no: in no wise: O no!
   [$E.$] Tell mee the reason thereof: tell mee the
cause thereof: tell me the subject: tell mee
wherefore.
   [$M.$] Because (as it seemeth to me) that by the
meanes of the grace, the fauour, and the
assistance of God, there is nothing done, or
ordained by him, but it is easily learned: I say
concerning tongues.
   [$E.$] Notwithstanding men say, That the
Bible, the holy Scriptures, the holy Writs, the
holy Letters are very mysticall, and vneasie
to be vnderstood?
   [$M.$] Well yea of the euill liuers, and of those
which neglect the duty which they owe to
our Lord: but concerning the faithfull,
<P 177>
they bee but tales, that they vnderstand
them not: yea euen so well as they wish,
prouided they vse good diligence, therein
praying the Lord to reveale to them the true
sense thereof.
   [$E.$] But who forbids then that euery one
should reade it?
   [$M.$] The Romish Church, the Church of
Rome: the Popish Church: the Church of
humane traditions: the Church of men.
   [$E.$] Hath it beene forbidden of God? of
Iesus Christ?
   [$M.$] No neuer: but (contrariwise) it hath
been instituted for mens saluation (fearing
God) generally to all sorts of men, yong, or
old, so well men as women: so well boyes
as wenches: so well fathers as mothers: so
well children as seruants, and seruing maids:
so well men of Church, as men of the fields
or trades men.
   [$E.$] Why haue those men done that? tell me
the reason thereof?
   [$M.$] Ile tell it you? Couetousnesse is an euill
canker, which hath beene the cause of it,
and is yet cause of many other euils in the
world.
   [$E.$] Then that hath also beene cause that the
Lord hath excluded his Word from such
folkes?
   [$M.$] Yea: and hath blinded them in their
wickednesse yet more: because they haue
shut the gate on him, when hee hath
knocked, desiring (by great mercy) their well
and saluation.
   [$E.$] But Master, why bring you mee here the
passages of the holy Scripture, and sacred
things, when I demand you other vocables
of little consequence?
   [$M.$] It is for feare least all my Schollers should
neglect their owne duty towards their
Parents, and betters: to wit towards God first,
and his holy Word: and also to their Fathers
and mothers: Secondly, to their Superiours,
and folkes which they ought to reuerence:
thirdly, to keepe irrefragable amitie with 
their brothers and neighbours.
   [$E.$] Sir, I see then by that meanes, that
carelesnesse, and our lusts, are bad things: are euill
vices, obstacles, and lets, which hinder vs to
feare the Lord?
   [$M.$] Yes truely: truely yea: truely your
reason is good.
   [$E.$] Sir, doe not you tell mee also that those
cursed vices, those cursed lusts: our wicked
flesh: the fragile, fraile, and soft worldly
things: all sorts of cupidities doe hinder
vs to know the Word of God: the
heroicall renowne of vertue the chast, and manly
<P 178>
force (which we ought to enjoy betwixt the
yong age, vntill the age of Adolescence and
virilitie.
   [$M.$] Yea, I tell you the pure truth thereof: for
euery man that loseth the time after his lusts,
doth lose his courage: loseth his renowne:
loseth the force of his body: puts his bodie
in many dangers: strayeth himselfe from the
favours of God: tormenteth his conscience:
encurreth many excesses and scabs,
excrements, cathaires and euill humours.
Moreouer, dulleth his noble memory: putting
himselfe also in danger of the pockes, of
gangraynes, and vlcers which doe gnaw his
body: cuts him the thread of life before euer
he come to halfe age: where contrariwise,
he who feareth God (taking the time by the
end) and reading his Word: and betakes him
selfe to study, and to vertue (which bee the
true rudder of the faithfull, and generous)
shall sit among the learned, and graue men,
to giue counsell for the good and state of a
Common-wealth. Furthermore, the Lord
will fulfill him his Saying, dictated by the
holy Ghost, and by the mouth of his seruant,
and Prophet Dauid, Saying, &c.
[^VERSE OMITTED.^]
   [$E.$] Maister, doe not the debauches, and
our lusts hinder the bringing vp of
the youth [^SOURCE TEXT: yonth^] , our studies, and foraine tongues?
as the Latine, the French, the Italian, and
many other.
   [$M.$] Truely child, there is no doubt of it: for
what more honour can men get in the
world then to know to speake foraine
tongues? since that by S=t= Pauls own mouth
esteemes them worthy to be learned, calling
them the grace, and the gift of the Lord.
<P 179>
   [$E.$] Maister, is the French tongue very
needfull, and profitable among the Nobilitie?
   [$M.$] Yea, and yet more profitable among the
Merchants: for except it be the Latine: me
thinkes, it is the most profitable of all
Christendome: and almost, it is so much in vse
(if I durst say it) as the Latine, and rather
more.
   [$E.$] Is it so easie, and docile to bee learned as
the Latine?
   [$Ma.$] Yes, much more: yea more then the
halfe.
