[}THE GREAT ORCHARD OF
RECREATION:
COMPOSED & GATHERED OUT OF SUNDRY DUTCH AUTHORS,
AND AFTERWARD TRANSLATED, AND DIUIDED INTO TWELUE CHAPTERS,
(^BOTH IN FRENCH, AND ENGLISH^) .}]

[}THE RISING IN THE MORNING, THE CLOATHING,
AND GOODS OF THE CHAMBER; AND SOME
OTHER BUSINESSE PARTAINING TO THE
SAME. BETWEENE NALANO,
TORQUATO: AND RUPSA SERVANT.
THE FIRST CHAPTER.}]
   [$ (^N.^) $] Ho! Master Torquato, will
you sleepe all the day
long?
   [$ (^T.^) $] Who is there? who cals
me? who demands me?
   [$ (^N.^) $] One of your Friends: a
friend: it is I, are you vp?
   [$ (^T.^) $] Who are you? what demand you? what
seeke you?
   [$ (^N.^) $] Good morrow Master Torquato:
doe you sleepe yet?
   [$ (^T.^) $] Ah Master Nalano, excuse me, I will
rise presently.
   [$ (^N.^) $] Rise at your ease, I will stay for you.
   [$ (^T.^) $] I will come presently and open you
the gate.
   [$ (^N.^) $] Not so in haste: be not so hasty: doe
not hast you so much.
   [$ (^T.^) $] Behold the gate is open, doth it please
you to enter?
   [$ (^N.^) $] God giue you a good morrow.
   [$ (^T.^) $] And to you in like manner Sir: you
are most heartily welcome.
   [$ (^N.^) $] I kisse your hands very humbly: were
not you yet risen?
   [$ (^T.^) $] No truly Sir, it is not yet so late.
   [$ (^N.^) $] Are not you ashamed to be so long in bed?
   [$ (^T.^) $] I did not sleepe: I did but slumber.
   [$ (^N.^) $] It seemeth to mee that you are yet sleeping?
   [$ (^T.^) $] For to say the truth, I am not yet well
awaked.
   [$ (^N.^) $] Ah if sluggishnes were vertue; how
many vertuous should there be in the world?
   [$ (^T.^) $] It should be pity: for I should bee of
that number.
   [$ (^N.^) $] Now haue you made goods: can you
also make the man?
   [$ (^T.^) $] I make the man, and leaue the goods
to be made by others.
   [$ (^N.^) $] But how haue you reposed this night?
<P 182>
   [$ (^T.^) $] Well: but I haue had many dreedfull
dreames.
   [$ (^N.^) $] Friend of the Muses, you should haue
risen at the breake of day.
   [$ (^T.^) $] So am I accustomed to do: but I went
late to bed yesternight.
   [$ (^N.^) $] But what do you? why do not you rise?
   [$ (^T.^) $] Ho Rupsa, come hither: Where art
thou? what doest thou?
   [$ (^R.^) $] Behold I am here: what doth it please
you! what demand you Sir?
   [$ (^T.^) $] Open me that window there, and giue
me my cloathes.
   [$ (^N.^) $] Sir, what cloathes doth it please you
to put on to day?
   [$ (^T.^) $] Giue me first a cleane shirt, and one of
the finest.
   [$ (^R.^) $] Sir, there is but two of them cleane.
   [$ (^T.^) $] Where be all the other? where be all
my cleane shirts?
   [$ (^R.^) $] Sir the Landresse hath six of them.
   [$ (^T.^) $] How many haue I in all?
   [$ (^R.^) $] Sir, you haue some three dozen.
   [$ (^T.^) $] Then I want foure.
   [$ (^R.^) $] Excuse me Sir, behold here yet some foule.
   [$ (^T.^) $] Cause them all to bee washed for to
morrow.
   [$ (^R.^) $] Ile send them: Ile cause cary them
to the Landresse to morrow.
   [$ (^T.^) $] Dispatch thee: giue me a cleane shirt.
   [$ (^R.^) $] Sir, what ruffe-bands will you weare
to day?
   [$ (^T.^) $] Those of battiste linnen, or of Cambricke.
   [$ (^R.^) $] Sir, will not you weare falling bands?
   [$ (^T.^) $] No: giue me a ruffeband, it is more
warme about my necke.
   [$ (^R.^) $] Sir, here is a ruffe for you.
   [$ (^T.^) $] Loggerhead, seest not thou that it is
all wet?
   [$ (^R.^) $] Sir, forgiue it me, for I tooke no heed
to it.
   [$ (^T.^) $] Goe and warme it in the Kitchene.
   [$ (^R.^) $] Sir, there is no fire there.
   [$ (^T.^) $] Make only a blaze with a little sticke
of wood.
   [$ (^R.^) $] Sir, here it is, put it on the while it is
warme.
   [$ (^T.^) $] Take heed there be small strings on it.
   [$ (^R.^) $] Sir, there are on both sides.
   [$ (^T.^) $] Giue me my Wastcoat quickly.
   [$ (^R.^) $] Sir, which will you haue? the wollen
one?
   [$ (^T.^) $] No: giue me the knit one.
   [$ (^R.^) $] Sir, what cloathing doth it please you
to weare to day?
   [$ (^T.^) $] Those of white satin laid with gold lace.
   [$ (^R.^) $] Sir, they lacke, I know not how many
buttons.
<P 183>
   [$T.$] Put them on presently.
   [$R.$] Sir, I haue neither needle, threed nor
thimble.
   [$T.$] Goe to the Taylor and borrow one.
   [$R.$] Sir; Ile repaire them for to morrow.
   [$T.$] Master Nalano, doe not thinke long.
   [$N.$] No, no, sir: in the meane time Ile reade
in this booke.
   [$T.$] Boy, giue me rather my sute of taffata,
for it is warme weather.
   [$R.$] Sir, it is in the bottome of the Trunke.
   [$T.$] You euill boy, why dost not thou take
it out?
   [$R.$] Sir, I did not thinke you should haue
worne it any more, because it is too narrow
for you, and is all worne.
   [$T.$] Giue me then which thou wilt.
   [$R.$] Sir, here is your sute of cut fustian.
   [$T.$] Where be the Brushes, that I cannot see them?
   [$R.$] Sir, see them there tied to that naile.
   [$T.$] Where is the count of all mine apparell?
   [$R.$] Sir, they are all in your Trunckes and
Coffers.
   [$T.$] Bring it me quickly: reade it to me,
quickly.
   [$R.$] Sir, See there [^SOURCE TEXT: rhere^] is first a long      #
night Gown,
lyned, and furred with Martinskins. 
[^LIST OF CLOTHES OMITTED.^]
   [$T.$] Where is the rest? Is there no other thing?
   [$R.$] Sir, the rest is here vp and down the
Chamber.
   [$T.$] Make shift to finde out the rest,
otherwise keepe you well from my hands.
   [$R.$] See here be yet two paire of Bootes,
the one of Spanish leather, and the other of
Neats leather. A paire of Spurs. Three paire
of Boothoses. A paire of Pantofles. Your
Pumpes. Your night slippers.
   [$T.$] Where is all my Linnen, great and small?
   [$R.$] Sir, all is in that great Box there.
   [$T.$] Go you (Senselesse) look if all be there.'
   [$R.$] Sir, I cannot find the key.
<P 184>
   [$T.$] Carelesse body that thou art, where
hast thou layed it?
   [$R.$] I put it this morning in my Pocket:
Ha Sir, I haue found it.
   [$T.$] Art thou [^SOURCE TEXT: rhou^] so poore of memorie?
   [$R.$] Sir, I remember not so far as between
my mouth and my nose.
   [$T.$] Thou shalt neuer make a lodging of
three house height.
   [$R.$] Sir, can I make a good one, of one
onely?
   [$T.$] I beleeue, three Trees shall suffice
thee to make them.
   [$R.$] Sir, neuerthelesse great men come
(very often) to dwell in such little lodgings, and 
low houses.
   [$T.$] By the Body that I will not sweare, if
I lay my hand on a codgell, Ile make thee
stay in thy right senses.
   [$R.$] Sir, I can serue you no other wayes.
   [$T.$] Thou wilt that I take a log of wood,
and swinge thee with it ouer thy backe, or
about thine eares.
   [$R.$] Sir, God keepe you from doing so: I
would not you did that, for much.
   [$T.$] I see well now, that he who is bad of
Nature, is bad vnto the graue, if God hath
not called him.
   [$R.$] Sir, see here be a dozen of shirts. 2 doze~
of hand kerchers. As many [^SOURCE TEXT: may^] of fallingbands.
Eight ruffe bands with their Cuffs wrought
with silke. Foure Napkins. Six drinning
cloathes. Eight quoifes. 3 paire of sheets.
And yet in that combe case, be your combes
of Box, and of Iuorie. Your litle Sizars, with
your eare-pikers, Pick toothes, small forks:
and other things pertaining to the same.
   [$T.$] I see now that thou art an honest man:
thou hast found it.
   [$R.$] Sir, see here bee yet two dozen of
points.
   [$T.$] Set this Coffer, and this truncke from
thence, for they be too hote.
   [$R.$] Sir, will you weare shooes to day, or
bootes.
   [$T.$] No, giue me the shooing horne to pull
on my shooes.
   [$R.$] Sir, doth it please you that I pull them
on to you?
   [$T.$] No, thinkest thou that I am so lazie?
   [$R.$] What know I? it should neither bee
meruell nor miracle.
   [$T.$] Trusse vp my points loosly, and not
with hard bound knots, for to make me cut
them.
   [$R.$] Sir here is one that is not tagged.
What Girdle doth it please you to weare to
day?
   [$T.$] Reech me that embrodered with gold,
and my sword Hangers of the same.
<P 185>
   [$R.$] Sir, doth it please you to weare your
Rapier and Poniard to day?
   [$T.$] Yes, yes, giue me my Rapier and
Poinard.
   [$R.$] Sir take this sword, for it is lightest,
   [$T.$] Giue me my Sword made of the
Ferrara, and Italian Fashion.
   [$R.$] Indeed, sir, it hath a faire hilt, and very
light.
   [$T.$] Reech mee the Combe, for to combe
my haire.
   [$R.$] Sir, looke there is your come case
vpon the Window.
   [$T.$] Where be my gloues? I see them not.
   [$R.$] Sir, you forgot them yesterday in some
part.
   [$T.$] Go to the Glouer, and by me a paire of
kidleather.
   [$R.$] Sir, will you haue them perfumed?
   [$T.$] I care not, prouided they keepe my
hands fresh and delicate.
   [$N.$] My God! you are long a dressing
you.
   [$T.$] Sir, who goes softly, goes surely and
safely: I come presently.
   [$N.$] But Sir, what doe you with so many
garments?
   [$T.$] I cloath the~ according to the weather.
   [$N.$] How many haue you to change?
   [$T.$] Sir, I haue for to change one euery
day in the weeke.
   [$N.$] You do not go cloathed as I do? to wit
like a figure, and alwayes of one fashion.
   [$T.$] Truly sir, you do it for your pleasure,
and not of necessitie.
   [$N.$] How many sorts haue you of them?
   [$T.$] Sir, I haue but of Veluet, of Satin, of
Damaske, of Grogeram and of Fustian.
   [$N.$] Sir, you are very happy to enjoy of all
your commodities so ready.
   [$T.$] Yea it is you sir, who enjoyes the
pleasures of the world!
   [$N.$] No sir, it is you who can pisse in the 
bed, and say you haue sweat in it.
   [$T.$] Sir, I haue nothing but it is at your
commandement and seruice.
   [$N.$] Sir, I doe acknowledge it, and thanke
you very humbly for it.
   [$T.$] Sir, I do not as many doe, who thinke
neuer to be cloathed, if they haue not their
warderobes and trunkes full.
   [$N.$] Truly (may bee) Sir, those men haue
their cloathing furred with great debts.
   [$T.$] Sir, behold therefore, I content my selfe
with these few that I haue.
   [$N.$] Who is content of a little, enjoyeth                       #
[^SOURCE TEXT: enjoyerh^] al
things.
   [$T.$] A content heart, is a good cloake for
his shoulders.
<P 186>
   [$N.$] Sir, Why do you cloath you so
warmlie.
   [$T.$] For to liue as it shall please God, and
to follow the Prouerbe.
   [$N.$] How do you say that Prouerbe?
   [$T.$] Cloathe thy selfe warmly: eate oft and
little: drinke now and then (if God please)
and thou shalt liue long.
   [$N.$] Truly Sir, hee who can doe his owne
affaires, will doe another mans worse.
   [$T.$] He who doth his owne affaires,
defileth not much his hands with them.
   [$N.$] Sir, if it please you, let vs dispatch, and
hast vs a little.
   [$T.$] The greatest haste is the least worke,
and by spurring to much [^SOURCE TEXT: muchs^] make the flight 
the longer. Ile be more handsome to pare
my nailes.
   [$N.$] Sir, you anger mee to make mee
languish so long.
   [$T.$] Sir, I haue not yet washed my face, nor
my hands: nor I haue not trussed me.
   [$N.$] Sir, are you euery day so long in bed?
   [$T.$] Yes sir, sometimes, according as I goe
to bed.
   [$N.$] You annoy me very much to make me
stay for you, and wishing so long for your
most agreeable company!
   [$T.$] Sir, but what be the mortell paines?
   [$N.$] To stay for those that come not: to be
in bed and sleepe not: to serue and please
not: to haue a horse that goes not: to stray
when one desires not: to be at a gate when
they open not: and to haue a friend that
betrayes thee: are six things for to kill
thee.
   Truly Sir, those bee the paines which I
endure, and haue endured very often.
   [$R.$] [^SOURCE TEXT: E.^] In good truth Sir, I endure the first of
them at this present houre.
   [$T.$] Sir, beleeue me, you shall endure it no
more, for I haue done.
   [$N.$] God be praised, haue you once done?
   [$T.$] Sir, doth it please you to take a cup of
wine before you goe forth?
   [$N.$] Sir, it should be no great sinne.
   [$T.$] Are you accustomed to drinke in the
morning, or to make collation?
   [$N.$] I accommodate my selfe with all
things, and I am like a Millers sacke, and not
as some doe whiles, making consciencce to
spit in the Church before folkes, & would
doe worse if none should see them.
   [$T.$] Ho Rupsa, bring vs hither some
drinke.
   [$R.$] What is your pleasure Sir, doth it please
you to haue any thing?
<P 187>
   [$T.$] Bring some bread, some wine, and a
napkin.
   [$R.$] Sir, I will bring them you presently.
   [$T.$] Rinse and wash the glasses and the
Cups.
   [$R.$] Well Sir, see there they bee faire and cleane.
   [$T.$] Poure in some wine, and giue vs some
drinke.
   [$N.$] Sir, I know not how you can drinke so earely?
   [$T.$] Very well Sir. This to your good
health.
   [$N.$] Sir, I loue it from you, and Ile pledge
you with a very good heart.
   [$T.$] Rupsa, giue some drinke to Maister Nalano.
   [$N.$] Sir, support me in that, for I drinke
not often out of meale time.
   [$T.$] Sir, the morning drinke is good for to
charme the mist.
   [$R.$] Sir, doth it please you to haue any
other thing?
   [$T.$] Giue me my sword, my poniard, and
my cloake: helpe me to gird them on me.
   [$N.$] Sir, that cloake doth become you
very well.
   [$R.$] Sir, shall I goe with you?
   [$T.$] No, not, dresse vp the Chamber, and
shut vp all.
   [$N.$] Sir, I pray you let vs loose no more
time.
   [$T.$] Sir, I am ready, goe before and I will
follow you.
   [$N.$] I had rather shew my selfe indiscreet,
then disobedient.
   [$T.$] Hola, Boy. follow me.
   [$R.$] Sir, I come, but I go first to shut the
gate and the doores.
   [$T.$] Thou saiest well: but shut them with
the keye.
   [$N.$] who shuts well, opens well.
   [$T.$] True, and who feareth God, falleth
neuer in mischance.

[}A DISCOURSE OF FAMILIAR SPEECH (VPON THE
WAY IN THE MORNING): WITH AN OTHER
PRETY DISCOURSE OF THE TENIS, BETWEEN THREE
FRIENDS: TO WIT, (^HENRY^) , (^IOHN^) , AND
