[^ONE OF THE THREE FRIENDS IS MISSING FROM THIS HEADING. 
THE FRENCH LANGUAGE HEADING HAS THOMAS, HENRY AND IEAN.^]

   [$T$] God giue you a good morrow, sir.
   [$H.$] And to you likewise sir, a good
morrow and good yeare.
   [$T.$] The Lord grant you a good morrow
Sir.
   [$H.$] Sir, the same be giuen vnto you with
all happinesse.
   [$T.$] Sir, God giue you all good lucke and
all prosperity.
   [$H.$] Sir, I wish you the same with a good
heart.
<P 188>
   [$T$] What are you going to doe so alone?
   [$H$] Sir, I would not be alone in Paradice.
   [$T.$] Notwithstanding it is better to be alone
then in euill company.
   [$H.$] He who betakes himself to be with you
is well accompanied.
   [$T$] Sir, how doe you doe this morning?
   [$H$] Sir, ready to doe you any seruice.
   [$T$] Sir how goes it with your health this
morning?
   [$H$] Sir, very well, at your
commandement.
   [$T.$] How haue you done since the other
day?
   [$H$] Sir, I haue done well, and found my
selfe well, praised be God.
   [$T.$] Truly sir, I reioyce alwaies of your
welfare.
   [$H.$] But whether are you bound to goe in
such hast?
   [$T.$] Sir, I take my way towards S. Paul his
Church [^SOURCE TEXT: Chutch^] .
   [$H.$] And you sir, whither goe you so alone?
   [$T.$] I will goe walke a little.
   [$H$] And you sir, so well as I, whither is it
that you doe goe?
   [$T$] Sir, I am going to the Exchange.
   [$H$] Sir, doth it please you to haue company?
   [$T$] Sir, very willingly, if I do not
importune you.
   [$H$] No truly sir, I shall be very glad of your
company.
   [$T$] And I sir, most glad of yours.
   [$H$] Sir, doth it please you that I keepe you
company?
   [$T$] Sir, you shall doe me great honour and
pleasure.
   [$H$] Sir, I would not trouble you so much.
   [$T$] No forsooth, sir, you should rather doe
me honour.
   [$H$] Sir, doth it please you to goe by land, or
by water?
   [$T$] Sir, it is euen as it shall please you, it is
all one to me.
   [$H$] If you finde it good, let vs go by water.
   [$T$] Sir, that which liketh you pleaseth mee
infinitely.
   [$H$] Where shall we then ship in?
   [$T$] Sir, at S. Paul his Key.
   [$H$] It is true, sir, a very commodious place.
   [$T.$] Sir, enter then into the Boat.
   [$H$] That will I not doe by no meanes.
   [$T$] Sir, doth it please you to enter into the
Boat?
   [$H$] Sir, to what end serue those ceremonies
betweene you and I?
   [$T$] Sir, I will enter then for to obey you.
<P 189>
   [$H$] We are happy to haue two such strong
men.
   [$T.$] Euen as the Carters do serue vs by land,
so also the mariners and watermen, doe vs
pleasure and ease by water.
   [$H$] Truly sir, I am of your opinion.
   [$T.$] How like you this going by water
in Boats?
   [$H$] Sir, indeed I take pleasure to goe by
water, but more to goe by land, and better
without danger.
   [$T$] Why? is it by chance that those horses
do please you that haue their bridles behind
them?
   [$H$] Truely sir, they doe not please me at
all, when I remember of a lesson that my
father was wont to tell me now and then.
   [$T.$] Sir, what lesson if it please you to tell
mee?
   [$H$] Well sir, he tould me often, When I
was able to goe by land, that I should neuer
goe by water.
   [$T$] Notwithstanding, men were wont to
say, That hee who trauelleth not by sea,
knew not what the feare of God was.
   [$H$] And also he who trauells not by land,
knows (no more) what solace, sport, and
pleasure is.
   [$H$] Sir, shall wee passe vnder the bridge
since that the tide goes forth?
   [$T$] Sir, to what vse are Bridges made?
   [$H$] To passe ouer them, and not vnder
them.
   [$T$] Why will you then wee passe vnder
them?
   [$H$] Ho, ho, sir, I vnderstand you well.
   [$T$] Where shall we take land?
   [$H.$] Sir, at the end of the Bridge if it please
you.
   [$T$] On this side, or yonder side of the Riuer?
   [$H$] Sir, as it shall be most commodious for
you.
   [$T$] On this side then, for to bee the neerer
the Exchange.
   [$H$] Sir, your opinion, What time of the
tide is it?
   [$T$] Sir, I know not if it flowes or ebbes.
   [$H$] Me thinks it flows, if I be not deceived.
   [$T$] Sir, what haue you to doe at the
Exchange, if it please you?
   [$H$] Sir, I am to dispatch some businesse
of mine.
   [$T$] Sir, what businesse haue you there to
bring to end?
   [$H$] Sir, I am to speake to a friend for some
worke of mine.
   [$T$] Sir, thinke you to finde him there?
   [$H$] Yea forsooth, for he did promise me
so yesterday.
   [$T$] On what side hath he assigned you to
finde him?
<P 190>
   [$H.$] Where the Italians do walke, or there
about.
   [$T.$] Think you that he wil keep his promise?
   [$H,$] Yes sir, for I take him to bee an
honest man.
   [$T.$] Who promises and keepes not is not to bee
trust to.
   [$H,$] Sir, you are in the right, but I trust to his.
   [$T.$] Good God keepe mee from those in
whom I trust, for I shall keepe me from
those whom I mistrust.
   [$H,$] Sir, he gaue me so good words, that
I could not refraine but trust him
   [$T.$] Doe not you know, that the wicked
deedes, and the faire words, doe beguile the
wise men so well as fooles?
   [$H,$] Sir, I know it well, but if he strike me
with his sword, Ile strike him againe with
my scabbert.
   [$T,$] Sir, you will then render him a loafe
for a cake.
   [$H,$] Sir, if it be possible, do neuer ill to
him that wishes you any, for by hatred
Nature is corrupted.
   [$T,$] Notwithstanding (Sir) the wicked
ought to be punished.
   [$H,$] It is true sir: but it is said, That to a
Wolfes flesh, must be giuen a Dogs tooth.
   [$T,$] Sir, what a clocke is it now?
   [$H,$] Sir, it is about ten a clocke.
   [$T,$] Sir, what houres be those that strike?
know you?
   [$H,$] Eleuen Sir, it is eleuen a clocke.
   [$T,$] Sir, what a clocke may it be?
   [$H.$] Sir, it cannot fail, but it must be twelue.
   [$T,$] Sir, Ile goe see at the Sunne Dyall.
   [$H,$] But (to the purpose) VVhere will you
dine to day?
   [$T,$] Truly (Sir) I know not yet where I
shall dine.
   [$H,$] Sir haue you made a promise any
where?
   [$T,$] Sir, in no wise, if I can remember.
   [$H,$] Sir, doth it please you wee dine
together?
   [$T,$] Sir, I desire no other thing.
   [$H,$] Shall we go then to some Ordinary?
   [$T,$] Sir, as it shall please you.
   [$H,$] Goe before and I will follow you.
   [$T,$] Sir, if it please you, Ile goe before and
guide you the way.
   [$T,$] Sir, God doth favour me much, making
me haue so honourable a Guide as you are.
   [$T,$] Sir, I beleeue we are come too late.
   [$H,$] Thinke not that, for it is yet very earely.
<P 191>
   [$T.$] Sir, doth it please you to stay for me a
little here, and Ile come presently againe.
   [$H.$] Sir, in the mean time Ile walke a turn
or two through the Exchange.
   [$T.$] Sir. let it not displease you, Ile go speak
with a Gentleman.
   [$H.$] Sir, truly with all Authority, and not
with licence.
   [$T.$] Now goe to, I haue ended my busines:
shall we goe home and dine?
   [$H.$] Sir, I pray you, for I haue a good 
stomocke.
   [$T.$] In good truth (Sir) that is a very good
token of Health.
   [$H.$] I giue God thankes, I finde my selfe
alwaies able and frolike of the body.
   [$T.$] Sir, and of your Purse, how do you 
feele it whiles?
   [$H.$] Sir, alwaies ill disposed and
languishing.
   [$T.$] Truly Sir, the disease is so common that 
euery one feeles it.
   [$H.$] Sir, haue not you drunke to day?
   [$T.$] Not yet Sir, and you?
   [$H.$] Sir, I goe neuer forth of my lodging
before I drinke a good Cup.
   [$T.$] I neuer vsed my selfe to it, but hence
forth I will doe it.
   [$H.$] My God Sir! see here Mr. (^Iohn^) comes
to see you.
   [$T.$] Truly it is he indeed, ah! Mr. (^Iohn^) ,
you are very heartily welcome.
   [$I.$] Sir, I kisse your hands very humbly.
   [$H.$] VVell my Masters, what shall wee doe
vntill dinner time?
   [$I.$] I agre to all things, provided wee doe
any thing.
   [$T.$] My maisters, Ile refer my selfe to the
Company.
   [$H.$] Let vs then make some game at the
Tenis.
   [$I.$] Iust, for this morning doth require it
being so cold.
   [$T.$] And there after we shall all go dine
together.
   [$H.$] And also after noone wee will goe see
some Comedy.
   [$T.$] How Sir, they are but repeating of old
Histories.
   [$I.$] Pardon me Sir, for in England are plaid
true Comedies.
   [$H.$] Yea Sir, and true Tragedies also, if men
would seeke them.
   [$T.$] My Masters, but let vs resolue to doe
something [^SOURCE TEXT: sometehing^] for to [^SOURCE TEXT: ro^]     #
flye from idlenesse.
   [$I.$] Let us then goe play at the Tennis.
   [$H.$] My Masters, then shall it bee needfull
that one of vs stand by.
   [$I.$] I will stand by, play ye two together.
<P 192>
   [$ (^T.^) $] Not so, if it please you wee will cast
