   [$ (^I.^) $] It is at my lodging with mine host and
mine hostesse.
   [$ (^T.^) $] Are you there by Moneth, or by week
with other table guests?
   [$ (^I.^) $] Yes Sir, we are there either by the
moneth or by the weeke, as we will: and wee
are vsed there like Princes, and very
ioyfully.
   [$ (^H.^) $] Truly Sir, you doe very well, for a
hundred thoughts shall neuer pay an ounce
of debt.
   [$ (^T.^) $] Sir, haue you alwaies there good
meat?
   [$ (^I.^) $] Truly, wee haue so much as sufficeth
for the food of our bodies.
   [$ (^H.^) $] Sir, haue you where withall to break
your fast in the morning?
   [$ (^I.^) $] Yes forsooth, sometimes (as to say) a
little bread and butter.
   [$ (^T.^) $] Truly you are in good case if you haue
no other thing.
   [$ (^I.^) $] You know well that he who is content
is merry.
   [$ (^T.^) $] In truth Sir, Ile come and see you one
of these mornings.
   [$ (^I.^) $] Sir. I pray you do it: do so much that
I may see you now and then.
   [$ (^T.^) $] And you, do in such sort, that we may 
enjoy your presence.
   [$ (^I.^) $] Sir, doe not doubt; but I will come
also and trouble you now and then. 

<S SAMPLE 2>
<P 233>
[}A MOST PLEASANT DISCOURSE OF AN EUILL
LODGING, AN VGLY AND HARD-FAVOURED WIFE, AND
A FAIRE AND HONOURABLE LADY IN BEAUTY:
WITH A COUNTERFAIT COMPLEMENT OF A
SLUGGISH LAZY BODY: BETWIXT IAMES
AND HIS SERVANT LIPPA.}]

[}THE EIGHT CHAPTER.}]
   [$I.$] This may be called a miracle that thou
art come so quickly againe.
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, to say the truth, I haue taried no
where.
   [$ (^I.^) $] What good newes hast thou heard?
hast thou done my Busines?
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, I did see Master M. but not Master
P. because he was gone abroad.
   [$ (^I.^) $] And what good newes hath Master M.
told thee?
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, what would you he should say?
you know well he is full of gentlenesse.
   [$ (^I.^) $] Child, I know it well, and so will I
praise him all my Life time.
   [$ (^L.^) $] Verily Sir, he deserues that men
honour him very much.
   [$ (^I.^) $] It is true: for he is so curious that hee
growes fat doing good to others.
   [$ (^L.^) $] Truly Sir, if he eate no other thing he
should be in a poore estate.
   [$ (^I.^) $] But what said he to thee?
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, hee rendreth you his Salutation
with double vsury, and thankes you kindly
for your good remembrance of him.
   [$ (^I.^) $] I am very glad that hee is in so good
Health.
   [$ (^L.^) $] Moreover Sir, he sayes, If he could but
set his foot abroad, hee would not faile to
come himselfe and kisse your hands.
   [$ (^I.^) $] Goeth not hee then yet forth of his
lodging?
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, with great paine can he stand on
his Feet, he is so weake.
   [$ (^I.^) $] What did hee for to driue away the
Time?
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, he was lying aboue his Bed,
playing on the Lute.
   [$ (^I.^) $] Knowest thou if he playes well or no?
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, what know I? I know no more
then a Swisser.
   [$ (^I.^) $] But how doth it seeme to thee?
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, according to my poore judgement
me thinkes he playes very well.
   [$ (^I.^) $] He playes also very well on the Violl,
on the Cister, Virginals, and on the Flute.
   [$ (^I.^) $] But what folks hath he in his lodging?
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, I haue seene no body there, but a
deformed, hardfavoured, foule, heavy, deaf,
blind, dumme, squint-eyed, blind of one eie,
vncleane and hideous Baud.
<P 234>
   [$ (^I.^) $] Verily! child, his house may then bee
called a Hell.
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, and yet worse, hauing such a
wicked wife in his lodging.
   [$ (^I.^) $] Hath shee beene faire heretofore?
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, you may well thinke! for shee is
cloathed like a Nunne, coiffed like a
Puppet, lame of one Arme, crooked of one
Foot, blinde of one Eie, the other
bleare-ey'd, hulch-backt, crumpshouldered, bald,
flat-nosed; and that little shee hath is all
wrinckled, and with great hanging Eares.
   [$ (^I.^) $] Alas! I have great compassion on him:
but what said she to thee?
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, all toothlesse as shee was, began to
raile and scould on me, giving mee injuries,
and disdaining mee on the Market place in
the sight of everie one (I being ashamed to
flee away) shee approched verie nigh mee
and gave me a terrible blast of her stincking
Breath.
   [$ (^I.^) $] It may be thou hast done some mischiefe
unto her, in dispraise of her beautie, or by
any bad or vndecent words.
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir excuse mee, for I had never seene
her before: and I beleeve there is not
such an intricate and vilde Drabbe in the
World.
   [$ (^I.^) $] O what terrible things thou makest me
beleeve!
   [$ (^I.^) $] Then shee is much vnlike one that I 
have seene to day.
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, how know you if she be fairer then
she that I have seene?
   [$ (^I.^) $] Because shee hath none of those Parts
that thou esteemest her to haue.
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, which bee the fairest parts that a
Woman ought to haue for to bee reputed,
and to make her verily faire?
   [$ (^I.^) $] They be three White, three Black, three
Red, three Long, three Short, three Big, three
Fine, three Narrow, three Broad, and three
Little.
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, make mee know that faire Worke
of God (in his Creatures) if it please you.
[^VERSE OMITTED.^]
<P 235>
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, thinke you that there are found
such Women ouer all where?
   [$ (^I.^) $] Yea, a thousand in this Towne, and
more.
   [$ (^I.^) $] Goe in the street and see if thou findest
Maister R. walking there.
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, I did see him goe towards his
lodging now presently.
   [$ (^I.^) $] Goe tell him that I would faine speake
a word with him: and knocke at the Gate,
to the end thou markest him well for to
know him an other time, when I send thee
thither.
   [$ (^L.^) $] Sir, I haue remarked him enough
already: but if you will command mee thither
any other thing, behold I am ready to
dispatch your [^SOURCE TEXT: yvur^] Commandements.
   [$ (^I.^) $] Goe then quickly and pray him that
hee would take the paines to come hither, if
it please him.



